<br>
Heh.  With the life cycles of typical hardware being 6 or 9 months, you can always say "wait a few months to upgrade".  Then you'll wait a few months, and someone else will tell you to wait a few more because something new is on the horizon.  In the end you'll be sitting with your 486DX2/66 system waiting and waiting.  :)<br>
<br>
Remember that when we talk about computer hardware, it's more like you're leasing the hardware than buying it, because in 6 months to 2 years most of it will be obsolete.  The money you spend is just for the privilege of using the hardware for a fixed period of time.<br>
<br>
As for nforce, it's still a bit of an unknown in the industry.  Actual production boards won't be out for a month or two at least, and they will likely be expensive.  It's also debatable whether the board will be worth upgrading to, and there are always issues regarding driver support for new chipsets.  Right now, the best AMD chipset is AMD's own 760 north bridge. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0> at: 7/23/01 6:11:22 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubrairwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brairwolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 221<br> <font color=#333399>(7/23/01 9:31:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1128.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Good Hardware Info site</span><hr size=1> Asus is saying they will have boards shipping in Oct and they are not the only ones.  I have been watching the nforce for a while now.  Just it would be a shame to lay out the cash for a nice high end DDR board when something that looks better is not very far off at all.  Most DDR boards are in the 175-200 range. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usorrun.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sorrun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><