Add some more ram and maybe a new hard drive and you get lots of bang for the buck. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1191<br> <font color=#333399>(7/24/01 7:31:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1128.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Good Hardware Info site</span><hr size=1> <b><i>One question I have right out of the gate is why do they designate DDR memory as "CAS 2" and "CAS 2.5"? </b></i><br>
<br>
CAS (column access strobe) is the number of clock cycles the memory waits to execute a transfer.  Memory running at CAS2 will wait 0.5 less clock cycles and therefore transfer data a tiny bit faster.  It's actually more of an operational guideline than a fixed setting on memory.  The reason I brought it up is that CAS2 isn't worth much more money unless you are looking into serious overclocking, so go with CAS 2.5, the more common type. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#333399>- </font><a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove>The Druids Grove</a><font color=#333399> - </font><a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot>General - OT</a> <font color=#333399> - </font><a href="http://www.thedruidsgrove.org">The Druids Grove</a><font color=#333399> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.9.4.8<br>Copyright ©1999-2002 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

